[
    {
        "content": "<p>Dear all,<br>\nI am reading Makkai and Paré's <em>Accessible categories</em> and in the first chapter, they define <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>κ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\kappa</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">κ</span></span></span></span>-filtered categories and write the following remark:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Note the easily seen fact that, for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>I</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">I</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">I</span></span></span></span> to be <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>κ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\kappa</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">κ</span></span></span></span>-filtered, it suffices to have the condition in 1.1.1 for the following specific graphs <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span>: the discrete graph on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>λ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\lambda</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">λ</span></span></span></span> elements, and the graph with two nodes and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>λ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\lambda</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">λ</span></span></span></span> many parallel arrows, both for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>λ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\lambda</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">λ</span></span></span></span> any cardinal <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>&lt;</mo><mi>κ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">&lt; \\kappa</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5782em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">&lt;</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">κ</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>where 1.1.1 is \"every diagram of source <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span> has a cocone\".<br>\nI thought I had a proof but as I am looking back on this part, I can't recover it. Do you know how I can prove this ? <br>\nin the finite case I see how to do it but for the infinite case it seems impossible to me<br>\nThanks !</p>",
        "id": 542978573,
        "sender_full_name": "Robin Jourde",
        "timestamp": 1759507516
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't immediately see it either.  One reduction I can see would involve discrete <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>λ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\lambda</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">λ</span></span></span></span>-graphs, parallel pairs of arrows, and the graph for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>λ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\lambda</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">λ</span></span></span></span>-sized \"wide pushouts\".  Another would involve discrete <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>λ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\lambda</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">λ</span></span></span></span>-graphs and the graph consisting of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>λ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\lambda</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">λ</span></span></span></span> parallel pairs of arrows all with the same codomain but different domains.</p>",
        "id": 542980952,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1759508255
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Does the corresponding <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/limit#ConstructionFromProductsAndEqualizers\">construction</a> for (co)limits work?</p>",
        "id": 542998138,
        "sender_full_name": "Elisha Goldman",
        "timestamp": 1759514277
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't think so, because constructing the two maps between coproducts that you then coequalize requires the universal property of the domain coproduct, whereas the cocones that merely exist in a filtered category don't have a universal property.</p>",
        "id": 543001074,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1759515401
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You can take a cone under the objects in the diagram, coequalize all of the parallel arrows from each object to the nadir (producing a wide span), put a cone under the objects in that wide span, and finally coequalize all of the arrows from the original nadir to the new one.</p>",
        "id": 543082683,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1759579460
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Where \"all of the arrows\" refers respectively to the arrows in the diagrams composed with the cocone morphisms and then the arrows constructed from the coequalizing arrows and the cocone arrows.</p>",
        "id": 543082778,
        "sender_full_name": "Morgan Rogers (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1759579547
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Ah, that's what I was missing!  Thanks Morgan.  I recorded this at <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/filtered%20category\">[[filtered category]]</a>.</p>",
        "id": 543098304,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1759593704
    },
